May the weekend find you breathing in the scent of the forests, splashing in water, climbing a cliff or watching an owl. Wherever you may be please keep in mind that we share outdoor spaces with other people, wildlife and plants. Be mindful of others.

Thanks @katieboue for the motivation!

#respect
#😌be good 🙏🏼 be kind 😊 be happy

@noapproachnate is a climber from Columbus, OH. The language of belay (full trust in your partner), send (goal orientation) and “I’ve got you” (the bond that connects) translates to the social equity movement we are experiencing and participating in. 
His post about why we need to speak up and make space in our social media conversations for this movement resonated. Hopefully you’ll take five minutes to listen to his voice, consider your action (or lack of) and become part of how we realign the United States by eliminating systemic racism. 
If you are white and reading this consider your actions. Is this moment in time making you feel guilt  and shame? Are you defensive and rationalizing your avoidance of action because you have prioritized your emotions over those that are suffering? 
Take action today. Sign a petition, contact your elected officials, be open to conversation, start conversations, understand white privilege and amplify your voice. Nate and millions of others are counting on us.

node.text:
David Roberts, Galen Rowell and Ed Ward climbed the East Face of the Mt Dickey in the Ruth Gorge of the Alaska Range in 1974. The team spent four days enduring weather and less than optimal rock. 

The East Face of Mt Dickey is a daunting challenge, it was a dozen years before another team ventured on to the face. 

David passed away on the 20th of August 2021 after a damn worthy struggle with throat cancer. He is survived by his wife Sharon and his brother Jon. While David's ability to shape an narrative of adventure with words set the bar for outdoor writers, he was a climber first and foremost. The Huntington and Denali expeditions, done alpine style, were ahead of the standard of the time. His climbing influenced his writing which in turn influenced the outdoor and adventure communities.

Twenty two years ago David was writing about the Mallory and Irvine  Research expedition. We went bouldering in Ilium, Colorado one afternoon. After he suggested collaborating on a book, a wild  energy took hold of David. He sent the problem he was working on and immediately started planning the project before we stumbled back to our car.

David's writing covered more than climbing. There was always a connection to life and mortality, something that David experienced while climbing. It's the time we spent together and the friendship we created.

You've done well David. 

Mt Dickey photo by @rousseaualan via @americanalpine 
Additional photos by Matt Hale via @bostonglobe

Sioux Chief Arvol Looking Horse, Gray Horn Butte, 2016

Today is World Indigenous Day. May we take a moment to reflect.

In the United States the Minnesota government recently approved the Line 3 pipeline to move tar sands over traditional lands. We need to move away from fossil fuels and bitumen leads this. 

From stopline3.org:

"All pipelines spill. Line 3 isn’t about safe transportation of a necessary product, it’s about expansion of a dying tar sands industry. Line 3 would contribute more to climate change than Minnesota’s entire economy. Minnesota’s own Department of Commerce found our local market does not need Line 3 oil. We need to decommission the old Line 3 and justly transition to a renewable, sustainable economy.  Line 3 would violate the treaty rights of Anishinaabe peoples and nations in its path — wild rice is a centerpiece of Anishinaabe culture, it grows in numerous watersheds Line 3 seeks to cross. It’s well-past time to end the legacy of theft from and destruction of indigenous peoples and territories."

@amyklobuchar @tinasmithmn @walzforgovernor 
@joebiden

@jimmychin • Photos can take us anywhere the photographer wants. The instant in which the artist releases the shutter, a fraction of a second or seconds later a two-dimensional image becomes a time stamp of that exact moment.  How the photographer, using the same tools available to all of us, creates art is the difference between the exceptional and the mundane. Our imagination is left to wander places, be it from the ravages of war or the celebration of life, courtesy of the photographer. What, where, how and why was the moment the photographer created the image?  How do our own lived experiences, which shape our views, influence what we see in the image? The best photography can transport us to a place that opens our minds, a flywheel for creativity and a deep sense of calm. 

	Jimmy Chin’s photography takes us to places where we are guests. Held tight by the cold, buffeted by wind, anchored by gravity and a foundation for self-reliance all add to the mystique of being in the wild. It takes effort. Layer up the difficulties of working with camera gear and it is truly rare the person that can create art with landscape, light and people.

"There and Back" is a window into Jimmy's photography.  It's the type of book that will be a foundation for your own creativity- be it with a camera or gravity. "There and Back" goes on sale 16th of November 2021

If you like first editions and certainty, you can order one today.

"As children, we are aware of time in a peripheral sense. Our first connection is night. Our parents encourage us to be quiet and still. Not knowing the structure of time as an infant, we think it’s perfectly fine – to our parents’ dismay – to ask for food or to test out our newfound vocal cords at all hours of the evening. In a few years, we grasp time, and it becomes less abstract. Concepts such as past, present, and future begin to take shape. The past equates to the olden days, the realm of grandparents. The present is playing with your friends, right now. And future is that magical day of birth that is rewarded with toys and cake.

As we enter school, time takes on a whole new meaning. Bells and clocks structure the daily routine in a world of painted cinderblocks, chalkboards, alphabet garlands, and linoleum. Our teachers are tasked with teaching time, beginning from age five. We enter kindergarten learning about time and are able to read time as a foundation for first grade. When I was in kindergarten the only clocks were round analog units, steadily watching over us. They were the silent sentinels that worked in concert with piercing bells to let us know time was shifting. Learning to glance at the clock and figure out where the big hand and small hand was a big deal. Once we made the connection between time and the rewards and punishments associated with an intangible entity that would shape our lives, we took clocks seriously."

Musings on time and the teenage need to have something.

Check out @hodinkee for the full essay.

Help Brown Girls Climb Level Up To Continue Operations💁🏾‍♀️

Brown Girls Climb came about to provide a space for Women of Color in the rock climbing world. We’ve brought you community gatherings across the country for five years. Now the need to find a way to level up our operations if they want to continue their mission. In other words, they need to turn our organization into a viable business or else Brown Girls Climb will sadly cease to exist.

@paulnicklen is passionate about photography. He is even more passionate about the ocean. Yup - the big salt that effects our life even if you live far from it. You might be one of the 7.1 million people that follows him. If so you are aware of his work to protect wildlife through his photography. 

Today is his birthday. Like all of us reading this, we are dependent upon nature for our existence. Oxygen, water and food - they come from nature. Paul gets this and is using this moment to get you connected to @sealegacy and @onlyone. 

The first image is courtesy of Paul. Orca fins on a tranquil sea. It's top drawer images like this that open our eyes to the marine world. The second image is mine. (Obviously) While climbing @thecliffslic in 2018 a dog entered the belay zone. With no hesitation this cute dog has a full love in with Paul. Maybe he smelled like seal. My guess is Paul is more animal than most people. This non verbal communication has allowed him to gain the trust of wildlife. Check out his page for some amazing images that took patience and courage to snap.

Remember - wildlife cannot advocate for their existence in the halls of government - the very institutions that affect their life. It's up to people like Paul and @mitty to speak for them. Their images speak loud. 

Join #thetide

From @browngirlsclimb : 
Navigating the ‘outdoor industry’ brands is a challenge and we know that limited resources exist to find the products and companies that fit your values and needs. 

Currently, there is limited data on the number of Black and Brown, Women, and Queer entrepreneurs in the outdoor industry. This lack of representation doesn’t match the changing demographic of outdoor recreationalists and the general population in this country. The multicultural shopper holds trillions in spending potential and we know, together, we have the power to change the way our money is invested.

Additionally, within large companies to small, finding products that fit our bodies and our values is a growing challenge for everyone wanting to experience their version of the ‘outdoors’. Corporate responsibility initiatives and inclusive product development should be celebrated not hidden in hours worth of online searches. @browngirlsclimb(BGC) believes everyone should have access to information to guide their purchases, that’s why they created the @bgcmarketplace. 

The BGC Marketplace is a values based shopping experience for the outdoor lover, committed to a better future for all. This platform allows you to search the gear you need while supporting the causes you care about.

Created by the folks at Brown Girls Climb, a BIPOC women led collective and social enterprise, this tool is designed for us to navigate capitalism the best we can while investing in companies that are investing in us.

We/I welcome you to join this new initiative and the efforts of Brown Girls Climb, by supporting their @ifundwomen crowdfunding campaign. Find the link in our bio or at @browngirlsclimb

Each of us can change the way business is typically run. We/I believe that the BGC Marketplace is just one step towards the transformative change we hope to see in the future.

"Only the mediocre are always at their best." Quote by French writer Jean Giraudoux.

Knowing that our energy, physical and intellectual, ebbs and flows like the tides is nice place to start. Not every day is the special "summit moment" and nor should they be. We would burn out from the intensity. 

When we take time aside, not reacting to what society foists upon us, we have a chance to recharge. We are ready to create the moments that define our lives. 

Standing on a beach as wavelets sand one's toes, sitting under a tree listening to birds sing or laying on a rock in the middle the night watching the stars are small ways in which we can "defrag the hard-drive". Perhaps these simple, humble moments, where we can reflect upon the immensity of life, are sources of energy.
